Based on my comprehensive research, here are the findings on working range input sliders in UXP plugins:

---

## Working Range Input Sliders in UXP Plugins

### Option 1: Spectrum Slider (sp-slider) - Recommended

The `sp-slider` component is Adobe's recommended approach for sliders in UXP plugins.

**HTML:**
```html
<!-- Basic slider -->
<sp-slider min="0" max="100" value="50"></sp-slider>

<!-- Slider with label -->
<sp-slider min="0" max="100" value="50">
  <sp-label slot="label">Volume</sp-label>
</sp-slider>

<!-- Filled variant -->
<sp-slider min="0" max="100" value="50" variant="filled">
  <sp-label slot="label">Threshold</sp-label>
</sp-slider>

<!-- Disabled slider -->
<sp-slider min="0" max="100" value="50" disabled></sp-slider>
```

**JavaScript Event Handling:**
```javascript
// Change event (fires on mouse up)
document.querySelector("#mySlider").addEventListener("change", function(e) {
  console.log("Value:", e.target.value);
});

// Input event (fires during drag - may have limited support)
document.querySelector("#mySlider").addEventListener("input", function(e) {
  console.log("Value:", e.target.value);
});
```

**Key Attributes:**
- `min` - Minimum value
- `max` - Maximum value  
- `value` - Current/default value
- `variant="filled"` - Fills the left portion of the track
- `disabled` - Disables interaction
- `fill-offset` - Specifies which side of track to fill

---

### Option 2: Native HTML Range Input

**HTML:**
```html
<style>
  .slider-row {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: row;
    align-items: center;
  }
  .slider-row span {
    flex: 0 0 32px;
  }
  .slider-row input[type=text] {
    flex: 0 0 64px;
  }
  .slider-row input[type=range] {
    flex: 1 1 auto;
  }
  .spread {
    justify-content: space-between;
  }
</style>

<label>
  <div class="row spread">
    <span>Opacity</span>
    <span id="opacityValue">50%</span>
  </div>
  <input type="range" id="opacitySlider" min="0" max="100" value="50" />
</label>

<!-- Discrete steps -->
<input type="range" min="1" max="6" value="3" step="1" />
```

**JavaScript:**
```javascript
const slider = document.querySelector("#opacitySlider");
const valueDisplay = document.querySelector("#opacityValue");

slider.addEventListener("input", function(e) {
  valueDisplay.textContent = e.target.value + "%";
});
```

---

### Important UXP Limitations

1. **CSS Pseudo-elements**: UXP only supports `::after`, `::before`, and `::width`. The `::-webkit-slider-thumb` and `::-webkit-slider-runnable-track` pseudo-elements are **NOT supported** in UXP.

2. **Limited CSS**: UXP is not a browser and does not support all CSS properties. Custom styling of native range inputs via WebKit pseudo-elements will not work.

3. **Event Timing**: The `change` event only fires on mouse up. The `input` event may fire during drag but has inconsistent support.

4. **Spectrum Components Cannot Be Styled**: The `sp-slider` uses Shadow DOM, so custom CSS styling of the thumb or track colors is not possible through regular CSS.

---

### Workaround for Real-Time Updates During Drag

If you need real-time updates while dragging (for Photoshop specifically):

```javascript
// Use input event with specific BatchPlay options
document.querySelector("#mySlider").addEventListener("input", async function(e) {
  await batchPlay([
    {
      // your action here
    }
  ], {
    "synchronousExecution": true,
    "modalBehavior": "execute",
    "paintOptions": {
      "immediateUpdate": true,
      "quality": "draft"
    }
  });
});
```

---

### Recommendation for Premiere Pro UXP

Since custom CSS styling of slider thumbs/tracks is not supported in UXP, use the **sp-slider with variant="filled"** for the best native appearance:

```html
<sp-slider id="thresholdSlider" min="-60" max="0" value="-30" variant="filled">
  <sp-label slot="label">Silence Threshold (dB)</sp-label>
</sp-slider>

<script>
  document.querySelector("#thresholdSlider").addEventListener("change", (e) => {
    const threshold = e.target.value;
    // Use the value
  });
</script>
```

---

